I cannot run any flutter development application inside Android Studio 4.1 stable on iOS using flutter and am not sure if it is an issue with Android Studio or the Flutter plugin.  I am using macOS Catalina Version 10.15.7

I am able to build app within Xcode 12.0.1. 

When I try it states: 
```
Launching lib/main.dart on iPhone 11 Pro in debug mode...
Warning: CocoaPods not installed. Skipping pod install.
  CocoaPods is used to retrieve the iOS and macOS platform side's plugin code that responds to your plugin usage on the Dart side.
  Without CocoaPods, plugins will not work on iOS or macOS.
  For more info, see https://flutter.dev/platform-plugins
To install:
  sudo gem install cocoapods

CocoaPods not installed or not in valid state.
Error launching application on iPhone 11 Pro.
```
With that said I re-installed cocoapods using the following commands:
```
sudo gem uninstall cocoapods
sudo gem install cocoapods -v 1.7.5
pod setup
sudo gem install cocoapods 
```
//to get latest version 1.9.3

The cocoapods were still not recognized after these commands.  
I uninstalled and re-installed Android Studio.  
This did not change the outcome.  
I also tried the --pre version of cocoapods. No change.  

ran these commands:
```
sudo gem update
sudo gem clean cocoapods

pod --version
```

@taracell our best guess is that there's something going on with your local settings somehow, outside of the plugin, but we're not sure how to debug. You may want to try using VS code instead, which has many of the same functions (https://flutter.dev/docs/development/tools/vs-code). Opening Android Studio from the terminal worked for me: `open /Applications/Android\ Studio.app`

The issue is caused by PATH is not being set correctly when opening Android Studio from GUI - in particular it does not seem to include /usr/local/bin, which is why the `which pod` command is not found during `flutter run`.

Originally mentioned here: https://github.com/flutter/flutter/issues/54962#issuecomment-672578610

I was having this same issue (on Android Studio 4.1) only whenever I was adding any location related package. After trying everything for 2 days I reluctantly downloaded latest beta version of Android Studio i.e. 4.2 Beta 2 and to my surprise it just worked.

@hoonji thanks for the suggestion and the link!

Closing this as it's not a flutter issue.

For people having problems with PATH, be sure it is defined by your login shell. In `bash` terms, use `.bash_profile` (or one of the other documented files). Do not use `.bashrc` or other non-login start-up scripts.

On my system I use .zsh. Setting up .zprofile did not fix the problem. Creating a symbolic link from .bash_profile to .zprofile did fix my issue.
```bash
ln -s .zprofile .bash_profile
```

Since 'flutter doctor -v' works properly from your terminal window that means that your environment variables are setup properly when running from a terminal window.

If you have changed the "Terminal > General > Shells open with" preference to a specified "Command" then you may want to set that as the default shell for your whole system. You can do that running "chsh -s <comand>". For me I had to do "chsh -s /bin/zsh" so that the whole whole os knows what your default shell is. Closing and opening Android Studio then running "Tools > Flutter > Flutter Doctor" will tell you if that worked of course.

If you did not change your default shell or that did not work for you then you will have to do some more digging to find out where your current shell is getting the bulk of it's environment variables from.

If you execute a ps -al in your "Terminal" window one of the running processes should be a shell (like zsh, Fish, sh, Tcsh, Ksh, Ash, Dash, bash). More than likely you are running zsh, bash or sh on Mac OS X. You must find out where all your variables are coming from for that type of shell.

If you are running 'bash' that means that some or all of your variables are in another file besides .bash_profile
See https://tldp.org/LDP/Bash-Beginners-Guide/html/chap_03.html to find out the different configuration files. Most people end up putting their variables in .bashrc or .bash_profile. Then you must either copy those variables into .bash_profile

If the terminal you are using is not bash you must search the internet to find what/where the configuration files for your particular shell are.

I was using .zshenv for all my variables which is probably not a good practice. So I then moved the file using 'mv .zshenv .zprofile'
I then created a symbolic using 'ln -s .zprofile .bash_profile' as described above.

Doing this has the advantage of having my variables setup properly whether I am running 'zsh' as my shell or if the 'shebang' line forces a script to use bash.

I hope this information is helpful.

The overarching goal is to help the plugin to find your environment variables from the default system shell environment while not messing up any customizations you may have made.

Excellent write-up @dspells, thanks! There is one more thing to remember. Whenever you change .zprofile or .bash_profile you need to log out and log back in. Otherwise, the change won't be processed by the operating system.

You don't need to logout to use new .bash_profile
Just run "source ~/.bash_profile" and you are ready to go
@ikarelin That won't update the settings used by the IDE.
